1_0	0.64636367	WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Supreme Court struck down as unconstitutional a law giving the president a line-item veto, which let him cancel specific items in tax and spending measures.
1_1	0.31295763	Thursday's 6-3 decision said the law violates a stipulation in the U.S.
1_2	0.48164077	Constitution that requires every bill passed by the Congress to be presented to the president for his signature of approval or veto.
1_3	0.25367811	The court said the constitutional language does not allow what in effect would be partial vetoes.
1_4	0.15658352	The justices said that type of line-item veto could be authorized only by amending the Constitution, an arduous process done only 27 times in the document's 211-year history.
1_5	0.60397914	The line-item veto law was challenged by New York City and an Idaho potato growers' group after U.S.
1_6	0.53424488	President Bill Clinton vetoed provisions they sought that were granted by Congress.
1_7	0.30053179	Clinton was the first president to exercise a line-item veto, an authority sought by almost every president this century as a tool to limit wasteful politically based spending by Congress.
1_8	0.2332848	Congress enacted the veto in 1996, and Clinton used it 82 times last year.
