2_18	0.077010931	``(R)epeal of statutes, no less than enactment, must conform with Art.
2_19	0.22853959	I''. There is no provision in the Constitution that authorizes the President to enact, to amend, or to repeal statutes.
2_20	0.10458801	Both Article I and Article II assign responsibilities to the President that directly relate to the lawmaking process, but neither addresses the issue presented by these cases.
2_21	0.11551189	The President ``shall from time to time give to the Congress Information on the State of the Union, and recommend to their Consideration such Measures as he shall judge necessary and expedient''.
2_22	0.091883821	Art. II, 3.
2_23	0.077027496	Thus, he may initiate and influence legislative proposals.
2_24	0.23599117	(footnote 27) Moreover, after a bill has passed both houses of Congress, but ``before it become(s) a law,'' it must be presented to the President.
2_25	0.080754995	If he approves it, ``he shall sign it, but if not he shall return it, with his objections to that House in which it shall have originated, who shall enter the objections at large on their journal, and proceed to reconsider it''.
2_26	0.092569873	Art. I, 7, cl.
2_27	0.11805634	2. (footnote 28) His ``return'' of a bill, which is usually described as a ``veto,'' (footnote 29) is subject to being overridden by a two-thirds vote in each House.
2_28	0.36860935	There are important differences between the President's ``return'' of a bill pursuant to Article I, 7 and the exercise of the President's cancellation authority pursuant to the Line Item Veto Act.
2_29	0.15298616	The constitutional return takes place BEFORE the bill becomes law; the statutory cancellation occurs AFTER the bill becomes law.
2_30	0.11067439	The constitutional return is of the entire bill; the statutory cancellation is of only a part.
2_31	0.15075237	Although the Constitution expressly authorizes the President to play a role in the process of enacting statutes, it is silent on the subject of unilateral Presidential action that either repeals or amends parts of duly enacted statutes.
2_32	0.10033908	There are powerful reasons for construing constitutional silence on this profoundly important issue as equivalent to an express prohibition.
2_33	0.11484089	The procedures governing the enactment of statutes set forth in the text of Article I were the product of the great debates and compromises that produced the Constitution itself.
2_34	0.13409163	Familiar historical materials provide abundant support for the conclusion that the power to enact statutes may only ``be exercised in accord with a single, finely wrought and exhaustively considered, procedure''.
2_35	0.15045004	Our first President understood the text of the Presentment Clause as requiring that he either ``approve all the parts of a bill, or reject it in toto''.
2_36	0.16490763	(footnote 30) What has emerged in these cases from the President's exercise of his statutory cancellation powers, however, are truncated versions of two bills that passed both Houses of Congress.
2_37	0.13689752	They are not the product of the ``finely wrought'' procedure that the Framers designed.
2_38	0.31365967	. . . The Line Item Veto Act authorizes the President himself to effect the repeal of laws, for his own policy reasons, without observing the procedures set out in Article I, 7.
2_39	0.089198237	The fact that Congress intended such a result is of no moment.
2_40	0.21702052	Although Congress presumably anticipated that the President might cancel some of the items in the Balanced Budget Act and in the Taxpayer Relief Act, Congress cannot alter the procedures set out in Article I, 7, without amending the Constitution.
2_41	0.31026313	(footnote 40) . . . If the Line Item Veto Act were valid, it would authorize the President to create a different law, one whose text was not voted on by either House of Congress or presented to the President for signature.
2_42	0.14502255	Something that might be known as ``Public Law 105-33 as modified by the President'' may or may not be desirable, but it is surely not a document that may ``become a law'' pursuant to the procedures designed by the Framers of Article I, 7, of the Constitution.
2_43	0.20681786	If there is to be a new procedure in which the President will play a different role in determining the final text of what may ``become a law,'' such change must come not by legislation but through the amendment procedures set forth in Article V of the Constitution.
2_44	0.13385192	. . . (EXCERPTS FROM DISSENTS FOLLOW IN 2nd TAKE) nn FROM THE DISSENT By Justice Scalia Insofar as the degree of political, ``law-making'' power conferred upon the Executive is concerned, there is not a dime's worth of difference between Congress' authorizing the President to CANCEL a spending item, and Congress' authorizing money to be spent on a particular item at the President's discretion.
2_45	0.1126483	And the latter has been done since the founding of the nation.
2_46	0.090805311	From 1789-1791, the First Congress made lump-sum appropriations for the entire government ``sum(s) not exceeding'' specified amounts for broad purposes.
2_47	0.12490625	From a very early date Congress also made permissive individual appropriations, leaving the decision whether to spend the money to the President's unfettered discretion.
2_48	0.17398478	. . . Examples of appropriations committed to the discretion of the President abound in our history.
2_49	0.21884672	. . . Had the Line Item Veto Act authorized the President to ``decline to spend'' any item of spending contained in the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, there is not the slightest doubt that authorization would have been constitutional.
2_50	0.35597093	What the Line Item Veto Act does instead authorizing the President to ``cancel'' an item of spending is technically different.
2_51	0.08950441	But the technical difference does NOT relate to the technicalities of the Presentment Clause, which have been fully complied with; and the doctrine of unconstitutional delegation, which IS at issue here, is pre-eminently NOT a doctrine of technicalities.
2_52	0.16356434	The title of the Line Item Veto Act, which was perhaps designed to simplify for public comprehension, or perhaps merely to comply with the terms of a campaign pledge, has succeeded in faking out the Supreme Court.
2_53	0.16096463	The President's action it authorizes in fact is not a line item veto and thus does not offend Art.
2_54	0.097426467	I, 7; and insofar as the substance of that action is concerned, it is no different from what Congress has permitted the President to do since the formation of the Union.
2_55	0.096128799	FROM THE DISSENT By Justice Breyer In sum, I recognize that the act before us is novel.
2_56	0.076534589	In a sense, it skirts a constitutional edge.
2_57	0.091619994	But that edge has to do with means, not ends.
2_58	0.11532977	The means chosen do not amount literally to the enactment, repeal or amendment of a law.
2_59	0.17232409	Nor, for that matter, do they amount literally to the ``line item veto'' that the act's title announces.
2_60	0.13263887	Those means do not violate any basic separation of powers principle.
2_61	0.21268899	They do not improperly shift the constitutionally foreseen balance of power from Congress to the President.
2_62	0.11098573	Nor, since they comply with Separation of Powers principles, do they threaten the liberties of individual citizens.
2_63	0.084855214	They represent an experiment that may, or may not, help representative government work better.
2_64	0.17021637	The Constitution, in my view, authorizes Congress and the President to try novel methods in this way.
2_65	0.084749877	Consequently, with respect, I dissent .
